\par }{\f4 When you first start the game up under Windows, you will see three rows of rectangles.  These are places where cards will either be placed, picked up, or displayed.  }{\f4 
\par }{\f4 
\par }{\f4 The first two rows of rectangles deal with the human player (that's you!).  The leftmost rectangle in the top row is your Battle pile.  This is where you will play a Go to start the game, where the computer will play }{\f4\uldb Hazards}{\v\f4 
dhazard}{\f4 , and where you will play }{\f4\uldb Remedies}{\v\f4 dremedy}{\f4  or }{\f4\uldb Safeties}{\v\f4 dsafety}{\f4 
.  To the right of that is the Speed Limit rectangle.  The computer plays a Speed Limit here, and you play the End of Limit card (if you have one) to remove the Speed Limit.  The space to the right of this is where your Safeties, if any, will be shown.  (
}{\f4 
However, you play all Safeties onto the Battle pile, not here.)  The next rectangle to the right will contain the number of miles you have played.  This is where you play mileage cards.  Finally, the last rectangle in the top row is the Draw deck.  At the
}{\f4  s}{\f4 
tart of your turn, you can move the mouse cursor over this and click the left mouse button to add a card to your hand (assuming the deck isn't empty).  Those without a mouse can use the arrow keys to move the cursor, and the spacebar or the Enter key to s
}{\f4 elect with.}{\f4 
\par }{\f4 
\par }{\f4 The first seven rectangles in the second row represent your hand.  At the start of a turn, you will have six cards.  Once you draw a card, you must either play or discard a card to end your turn.  To play a card, first move the cursor over th}{\f4 
e card and click the left mouse button.  Now "drag" the card by moving the mouse (keep holding the left button down), then let go of the button to "drop" it on one of five other places (described either above or below) to play the card, or on the Discard 
}{\f4 Deck below and to the right of your hand to throw the card away.}{\f4 
\par }{\f4 
\par }{\f4 The last row of rectangles is identical to the first, except that it shows the computer's Battle, Speed Limit, Safeties, and Miles played.  At the far right is the Discard Deck.  This will }{\f4 
show the last card discarded by you or by the computer.  This can be useful in guessing what cards the computer has or doesn't have.}{\f4 
\par }{\f4 \page }{\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} wherecard}}{\fs16\up6  ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Where can a card be played?}}{\fs16\up6  +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 
\f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} 300}}{\fs16\up6  K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} Playing cards}}{\fs16\up6  }{\b\f4 Where can a card be played?}{\b\f4 
\par }{\f4 It depends on what card you have selected.  If you want to play a }{\f4\uldb Hazard}{\v\f4\uldb dhazard}{\f4 
 card on the computer, click on the card in your hand, drag it to either the computer's Battle or Speed Limit rectangle (the two squares on the left on the bottom row), and drop it there.  You }{\f4 
will not be able to do this if the computer is already stopped or has a }{\f4\uldb Safety}{\v\f4\uldb dsafety}{\f4  that protects against the Hazard you are trying to play on it.  You can play Safeties and }{\f4\uldb Remedies}{\v\f4\uldb dremedy}{\f4 
 on either of the first two squares on the left side of the top row.  Mileage cards, however, must be played on your Mileage pile (in the top row, below the word "Miles:").}{\f4 
\par }{\f4 
\par }{\f4 If you want to discard a card, drag the card to the "Discard:" pile.}{\f4 
\par }{\f4 
\par }{\f4 You can also double-click on any card in your hand to "smart-play" it.  If playing the card is a valid move, it will be played.  Otherwise it will be discarded.}{\f4 
\par }{\f4 
